w:r.w:t: Group 4: Thuy Nguyen, Jiayu Sun, Lester Tsai, Lishan Wang
Sponsor: Community Health Plan of Washington

Community Health Plan of Washington (CHPW) is a non-profit health plan organization that provides care management services to their members. However, it is difficult to identify the members that will opt into CHPW’s care management programs, which leads to a waste of limited outreach resources. In this study, we build diverse machine learning models to predict member engagement in CHPW’s care management programs and evaluate their prediction performance. We obtain a prediction accuracy of about 0.62 for all models using classification threshold 0.4 which balances the tradeoff between precision (about 0.5) and recall (about 0.55). We prove that the use of our predictive models will not introduce racial bias. Moreover, we extract features that are important to the prediction of member engagement from our models, which can increase our understanding towards member engagement.

Community Health Plan of Washington (CHPW) is a local, Washington-based Health Plan with long-established ties to communities throughout Washington State. It is a not-for-profit company governed by community organizations (Community Health Centers) and serves 300,000 members across Medicaid, Medicare Advantage, and Washington’s public option.

CHPW undertakes proactive outreach to identify and address behavioral, social, and medical needs. It provides care management services to its members, including programs such as Case Management, Disease Management, and Community Support Services. These care management programs particularly benefit the aging population, the low-income population, and those patients with chronic or complex conditions by reducing treatment costs, reducing the rate of hospitalizations, and eliminating unnecessary and redundant testing.

However, there are limited resources in CHPW, making it challenging to outreach to everyone. It is difficult to identify the members that will opt-in and engage in CHPW’s programs, which leads to inefficient allocation of limited care management resources. Therefore, the objective of this project is to develop prediction models to identify members who are most likely to respond to outreach efforts and use the information gained from these prediction models to prioritize the members as Case Managers outreach them. By accurately predicting members’ propensity to engage in those programs, the impact of outreach efforts can be increased by allocating limited resources to the most effective channels in CHPW. Also, by reducing the expense of outreach efforts, the savings can be used to fund other programs.
The datasets include information on demographics, line of business, health risk assessment, enrollment, claims, diagnosis data, risk score, and customer service calls.

Demographics, line of business, and enrollment data come from the enrollment files provided to CHPW by the Washington State, and they contain information members reported in their application to be enrolled in a health plan.

Health risk assessment data are collected directly by CHPW. CHPW sends the survey to members asking about their demographics, socioeconomic and health status. The surveys could be completed by mail or phone. The responses are imported into the data warehouse.
The providers and hospitals submit claims information to CHPW after a member visits them. The claims include the cost of the visit, the procedure done during the visit, and diagnosis information.
Diagnosis data contain the diagnosis information on a member. The information comes in the claims submitted by the providers and hospitals.

The risk score is calculated based on the Chronic Illness and Disability Payment System (CDPS) model developed by UC San Diego. CDPS is a diagnostic-based risk adjustment model widely used to adjust capitated payments for health plans that enroll Medicaid beneficiaries. The model uses diagnosis codes to assign chronic condition categories that indicate illness burden related to major body systems (e.g., cardiovascular) or chronic disease (e.g., diabetes). The risk score includes weights for all CDPS categories an individual has. The higher the number of chronic conditions, the higher the score is.

Members call CHPW customer service for various reasons, and the customer service representatives input the information about the call in an application. This information is later imported into the data warehouse.

All members outreached for Care Management Services in Washington State between March 2020 and November 2022. A member can be outreached at most three times until they respond to the phone call, and the outreach record corresponding to their response is included in the dataset. For members who never respond to the call, they are considered as “not engaged”, and their first outreach record is included in the dataset.

The primary outcome is engagement status. It is encoded as a binary variable indicating whether a member is engaged in at least one of the several specific activities such as Case Management, Population Health, Community Support Services, Transitions of Care, and In-home case. 38% of the observations in the dataset are engaged, while 62% are not engaged.

There are totally 96 explanatory variables in the dataset. A description of all these variables can be found in Table S1. 85 variables are used to fit machine learning models, excluding irrelevant variables (such as member ID) and variables with too much missingness (see 2.6 for more details). The descriptive statistics (stratified by engagement) of the 85 predictors used in model fitting can be found in Table S2.

To visualize the missing data, we plot the proportion of missingness for explanatory variables, as shown in Figure S1. For the 7 variables with more than 60% missingness, we remove them from our analysis. Then for the remaining variables with missingness, we check the distribution of missingness by engagement status to explore the missing data mechanism, as summarized in Table S3. It seems the missingness is associated with engagement status at least for some of the variables. Therefore, we use the “MissRanger” package in R to impute the missing data instead of simply using mean/mode imputation. This algorithm uses random forest models to predict and impute the missing values of each variable based on all the other variables (not including the outcome variable). Therefore, it tends to introduce less bias compared to mean/mode imputation.

Before building any models, all data are transformed into numeric or categorical variables. The data are randomly splitted into a training set (80%) and a test set (20%). This 80%/20% splitting is appropriate with a large sample size of more than 44,000 observations and a proportion of the positive outcome of more than 30%.

Based on the training data, we build four parallel classifier models to predict the engagement status of CHPW members in Washington State, including Lasso, random forest, XGBoost and BART methods. Those models are chosen because they are all very common machine learning models and are known to perform well on tabular data. These models are flexible and are appropriate for data with many features. And they can handle multicollinearity well. Moreover, we choose multiple models because these models are representations of different types of models, and they cover a broad range of complexity as well as a broad range of interpretability. Therefore, it makes sense to have a competition among those four models and finally select the best predictive model for the given data.

To optimize the performance of our machine learning models, we tune hyperparameters for each model using 10-fold cross-validation on the training data. After fitting each model with optimal hyperparameters, we evaluate their performance on the test set using multiple evaluation metrics including accuracy, precision, recall, specificity, F1 score, ROC curves with AUC value, precision-recall curves with AUC-PR value and calibration plots. Finally, we extract feature importance from each model.

Lasso is a penalized regression analysis method that performs both variable selection and regularization in order to enhance the prediction accuracy and interpretability of the resulting statistical model. Lasso is a relatively simple model and is fast to run. And it usually avoids overfitting. Some limitations of Lasso include that it assumes a linear hypothesis which may not be true, and the feature selection results can be biased sometimes. The hyperparameter we tune is the regularization term (lambda).

Random forest is an ensemble learning method that operates by constructing a multitude of decision trees at training time. For classification tasks, each tree in the random forest spits a class prediction, and the class with the most votes becomes the model’s prediction. Random forest allows for more variation amongst the trees in the model, thus avoiding overfitting. It is flexible, but it runs relatively slowly. And it loses some interpretability. The hyperparameters we tune include the number of trees in the forest, the maximum number of features considered for splitting a node, and the minimum node size.

XGBoost is an implementation of gradient-boosting decision trees. This algorithm has recently been dominating applied machine learning and Kaggle competitions for structured or tabular data. It’s fast, easy to use and yields high accuracy, but it can overfit sometimes, and it loses some interpretability. The hyperparameters we tune are the number of trees, tree depth, the number of selected predictors, the minimum node size, the minimum loss reduction, learning rate, and sample size proportion.

BART is a Bayesian “sum-of-trees” model in which each tree is constrained by a prior to be a weak learner. For binary response y, P(Y=1|X)=Φ(f(x)), where Φ denotes the standard normal CDF (probit link). With many trees, a sum-of-trees model gains increased representation flexibility which endows BART with excellent predictive capabilities. The disadvantages include a requirement of large memory and a loss of interpretability. The hyperparameters we tune include the number of trees in the sum-of-trees formulation, the power parameter for tree prior, and the base parameter for tree prior.

Accuracy is a metric that generally describes how the model performs across all classes. It is most useful when all classes are of equal importance. It is defined as the ratio between the number of correct predictions to the total number of predictions.

The precision measures the model’s accuracy in classifying a sample as positive. It is defined as the ratio between the number of positive samples correctly classified to the total number of samples classified as positive (either correctly or incorrectly). In this study, precision is an important evaluation metric considering that we want the members we outreach (classified as positive) to be engaged (true positive).

The recall measures the model's ability to detect positive samples. It is calculated as the ratio between the number of positive samples correctly classified as positive to the total number of positive samples. It is also important in this study because we want to identify members who will be engaged as many as possible.

Specificity measures the model’s ability to detect negative samples. It is defined as the ratio between the number of negative samples correctly classified as negative to the total number of negative samples.

F1 Score combines the precision and recall scores of a model by using their harmonic mean. Maximizing the F1 score implies simultaneously maximizing both precision and recall. F1 score is defined as (2 * precision * recall / (precision + recall)).

An ROC curve (receiver operating characteristic curve) is a graph showing the performance of a classification model at all classification thresholds. It plots true positive rate and false positive rate at different classification thresholds. AUC (Area under the ROC Curve) measures the entire two-dimensional area underneath the entire ROC curve and provides an aggregate measure of performance across all possible classification thresholds.

Much like the ROC curve, the precision-recall curve is a graph used for evaluating the performance of binary classification algorithms across many thresholds. It is constructed by calculating and plotting the precision against the recall for a single classifier at a variety of thresholds. It is often used in situations where classes are heavily imbalanced. AUC-PR stands for area under the precision-recall curve.

Calibration plots are used to check the performance of a model in terms of whether the distribution and behavior of the probability predicted are similar to the distribution and behavior of probability observed in data. To draw a calibration plot the following steps are followed: 1) create a data set with two columns that are the actual label and its predicted probability given by the model; 2) sort this data set in ascending order of the probability predicted by the model; 3) divide the data set in bins of some fixed size; 4) calculate fraction of actual positive in each bin and the average of probabilities predicted by the model; 5) plot a graph with fraction of positive on y-axis and average probability on x-axis.

The prediction performance of the 4 models when using a classification threshold 0.4 is summarized in Table 1. We find that the prediction performance is very similar among the 4 models, especially in terms of accuracy and F1 score. Unfortunately, the prediction accuracy is only 0.62 - 0.63 for all models.
Table 1: prediction performance of different models (threshold = 0.4)

Different classification thresholds are tried to predict engagement for all models. Precision and recall values for each threshold are recorded in Table 2. It is not surprising that precision tends to increase at the cost of decreased recall as the threshold increases. The most common choice of threshold, which is 0.5, can achieve the highest accuracy (which is 0.64 - 0.65, not shown in the table), but recall is only about 0.3 when using threshold 0.5. Therefore, we choose to use 0.4 as our classification threshold which balances the trade-off between precision and recall.
Table 2: prediction performance of models using different thresholds

ROC curves and precision-recall curves are the evaluation metrics of model performance independent of the choice of thresholds. We plot ROC curves and precision-recall curves for all models, as shown in Figure 1 and Figure 2, respectively. Both kinds of curves look very similar for different models. The AUC values of the 4 models are about 0.66 - 0.67, and the AUC-PR values of the 4 models are about 0.51 - 0.53. Therefore, we conclude again that the performance of our machine learning models are not good enough for the prediction of member engagement.

Figure 2: precision-recall curves for different models

To compare how well the probabilistic predictions of each model are calibrated, we make calibration plots for all models, as shown in Figure 3. It suggests that the random forest model is best calibrated and fits the data best, though it seems the prediction performance is not associated with how well the model is calibrated in this study. It is worth noting that the observed probability of the group with highest predicted probability is only about 0.6, which suggests that one possible reason to explain the low performance of our models is the intrinsic high degree of stochasticity in the data.
Figure 3: calibration plots for different models

CHPW cares about health equity. To make sure the use of the predictive models will not introduce racial bias, we check our models’ prediction results for different race groups, as summarized in Table 3. We find that the true engagement rate for different races is similar, suggesting that race is not an important factor that affects member engagement. It is shown that the predicted engagement rate is also similar among different race groups, which is true for all models (one exception is the group “Declined”, which has both low true engagement rate and low predicted engagement rate compared to other groups, but we do not take this group into consideration since it is not related to any specific race). Therefore, we believe that using predictive models to select members to outreach will not introduce racial bias.
Table 3: prediction for different race groups (threshold = 0.4)

Finally, we extract features that are important in predicting member engagement from each model. Table 4 shows the top 7 important features. We find that there is a big overlap in the features selected by different models, suggesting that these features are truly important. It seems that the line of business, which indicates which Medicare or Medicaid programs a member is from, is the most important one. Moreover, age, pregnancy status, risk score and risk level, the number of chronic conditions as well as several variables related to a member’s medical expense are among the most important ones.

We check how these variables are associated with member engagement according to Table S2. It is suggested that some specific health plans including “Apple Blind and Disabled”, “Apple Health Family”, “Expansion” and “Medicare” are positively associated with engagement, while the other plans are negatively associated with engagement. Another interesting finding is that the mean value of risk score, the mean value of revenue, the mean value of the number of chronic conditions and the proportion of pregnancy are all higher in people who are engaged than those in people who are not engaged. Therefore, it seems the members who are less healthy and in higher demand for medical services are more likely to be engaged.

Overall, the prediction accuracy is not high, but the models can still be helpful. To help CHPW identify the members who are most likely to be engaged, the new members can be ranked according to their predicted engagement probability, and the members with higher predicted probability can be outreached first. As shown in Table 1, the precision value when using threshold 0.4 is about 0.5, which means that about 50% of the members outreached will be engaged. This is better than a random selection of members to be outreached, where about 38% of the members outreached will be engaged.

Several possible reasons can explain the low prediction performance of our models. First, there are some sparse variables in the dataset, which may affect the model performance. More advanced machine learning techniques may be needed to overcome the influence of sparse variables and improve the prediction accuracy.

Second, it is possible that the dataset is lacking in certain features that are significant to the prediction of member engagement. For example, we don’t have individual-level information for some key demographic characteristics such as educational level. Moreover, some variables created from survey questions may be useful to prediction but are removed due to their high level of missingness (because many people are reluctant to complete the surveys). Therefore, we may be able to improve the model performance by trying to collect more relevant information and increase the response rate to surveys.

Third, it is possible that engagement is difficult to predict in nature, though some members can be somewhat more likely to be engaged than the others. One paper in 2015 (DOI: 10.1089/pop.2014.0121), which has a similar objective and uses similar methods compared to our study, obtains an accuracy of 0.76 in the prediction of engagement in the High-Risk Case Management program for Medicare members. Considering their data is a little unbalanced (21% engagement rate), this level of accuracy is not high enough. Therefore, it seems it is not easy to accurately predict member engagement.

We are able to extract some important features from our models, and the meaning of these findings needs to be further discussed with case managers in CHPW who have better domain knowledge. But it is worth noting that though knowing the important features can provide us a better understanding of member engagement, it is difficult to improve engagement in practice, because these variables are attributes of members and are difficult to manipulate.
